>>e136077a-dd5d-49bf-8fc6-0697bc4760a0
That's because windows has barely any permission management.

It doesn't matter if you go through all those hoops to hide your identity if your gateway into the internet has a direct connection with the FBI, does it? Install OpenWRT to solve that.

First of all check if your router is in this list, if it is, install OpenWRT.
https://openwrt.org/toh/start
It's a free software embedded linux distro primarily targeting routers and it does come with a router setup by default.  You will also in all likelihood get a boost to router performance since OpenWRT is much better than whatever your router's manufacturer has likely built for you.

If you have a 24/7 home server running an unix system, or if your PC is the only computer in the network, you may also consider running that as a router. Its (relatively, compared to those embedded home routers) powerful hardware will also allow you to do all sorts of neat things such as QOS prioritization and packet filtering if you so desire. People like using OpenBSD for this since it's secure, easy to use and has a nice firewall. Here's a gentoo wiki link so you can have an idea of what you need to do to use an unix system as a router.
https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Home_router



Anyway, if you have a dynamic IP and want to IP hop, you can unplug and plug back in your router. If you want to speed up the proccess because you're impatient, you can reach your router's command line (most home routers have at least telnet access with the same password as your shitty web interface, if you're using a good one it's probably ssh-only anyway) and bring down then up your interface pointing to the internet. On an openwrt router, that usually means "ifdown wan && ifup wan"
